I'll explain how the system works and what files you need for Part 3.

How the System Works
The Architecture:

K3d Cluster: Runs a lightweight Kubernetes (K3s) inside Docker containers on your VM
Argo CD: A GitOps continuous deployment tool installed in your cluster
GitHub Repository: Contains your Kubernetes manifests (YAML files)
Docker Hub: Hosts the application image (wil42/playground or your own)
The Flow:

You run your installation script → installs Docker, K3d, kubectl, creates K3d cluster, installs Argo CD
You configure Argo CD to watch your public GitHub repository
Argo CD reads the Kubernetes manifests from your GitHub repo
Argo CD automatically deploys the application (pulling the Docker image from Docker Hub) into the "dev" namespace
When you change the version in GitHub (e.g., from image: wil42/playground:v1 to v2), Argo CD detects the change and updates the deployment automatically
Files You Should Have
In P3/ (local project folder):

script_install.sh - Creates K3d cluster, installs Argo CD, configures everything
script_uninstall.sh - Cleans up the cluster
Possibly a README
In Your Public GitHub Repository:

deployment.yaml - Kubernetes Deployment manifest that specifies which Docker image to use (e.g., wil42/playground:v1)
service.yaml - Kubernetes Service to expose the application on port 8888
Optionally: application.yaml - Argo CD Application resource (or you can create this via kubectl in your install script)
Clarification About the Application
Your confusion is understandable! Here's what happens:

The Docker image is ALREADY on Docker Hub - either wil42/playground (pre-made) or your own image that you would push there separately
You DON'T deploy TO Docker Hub with a script
Your GitHub repo contains Kubernetes YAML files that REFERENCE the Docker Hub image
Argo CD reads your GitHub repo and deploys the application TO your Kubernetes cluster BY pulling the image FROM Docker Hub
Example flow to change versions:

Your GitHub repo has deployment.yaml with image: wil42/playground:v1
Argo CD deploys this to your cluster
You edit the GitHub file to image: wil42/playground:v2
Argo CD detects the change and updates the deployment automatically
https://argo-cd.readthedocs.io/en/stable/operator-manual/declarative-setup/
